<text top="87" left="55" width="40" height="13" font="font8" id="p1_t6" reading_order_no="3" segment_no="3" tag_type="title">Review<b>Microbial Cell Factories</b></text>
<text top="105" left="55" width="444" height="15" font="font9" id="p1_t7" reading_order_no="4" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">Potential and utilization of thermophiles and thermostable<a href="http://www.biomedcentral.com/info/about/charter/"><b>Open Access</b></a></text>
<text top="123" left="55" width="168" height="15" font="font9" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="5" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">enzymes in biorefining</text>
<text top="140" left="55" width="392" height="14" font="font10" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="6" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">Pernilla Turner, Gashaw Mamo and Eva Nordberg Karlsson*<b>Potential and utilization of thermophiles and thermostable </b></text>
<text top="176" left="55" width="471" height="8" font="font11" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="7" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Address: Dept Biotechnology, Center for Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, Lund University, P.O. Box 124, SE-221 00 Lund, Sweden<b>enzymes in biorefining</b></text>
<text top="190" left="55" width="345" height="8" font="font11" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="8" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">Email: Pernilla Turner - pernilla.turner@biotek.lu.se; Gashaw Mamo - gashaw.mamo@biotek.lu.se;</text>
<text top="200" left="55" width="216" height="8" font="font11" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="9" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">Eva Nordberg Karlsson* - eva.nordberg_karlsson@biotek.lu.se</text>
<text top="211" left="55" width="92" height="8" font="font11" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="10" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">* Corresponding author</text>
<text top="359" left="112" width="44" height="10" font="font12" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="20" segment_no="17" tag_type="title">Abstract</text>
<text top="374" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="21" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">In today's world, there is an increasing trend towards the use of renewable, cheap and readily<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&amp;db=PubMed&amp;dopt=Abstract&amp;list_uids=17359551">  </a></text>
<text top="386" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="22" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">available biomass in the production of a wide variety of fine and bulk chemicals in different<b>Abstract</b></text>
<text top="398" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="23" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">biorefineries. Biorefineries utilize the activities of microbial cells and their enzymes to convert</text>
<text top="409" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="24" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">biomass into target products. Many of these processes require enzymes which are operationally</text>
<text top="421" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="25" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">stable at high temperature thus allowing e.g . easy mixing, better substrate solubility, high mass</text>
<text top="433" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="26" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">transfer rate, and lowered risk of contamination. Thermophiles have often been proposed as</text>
<text top="445" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="27" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">sources of industrially relevant thermostable enzymes. Here we discuss existing and potential</text>
<text top="456" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">applications of thermophiles and thermostable enzymes with focus on conversion of carbohydrate<i>e.g</i></text>
<text top="468" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">containing raw materials. Their importance in biorefineries is explained using examples of</text>
<text top="480" left="112" width="386" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">lignocellulose and starch conversions to desired products. Strategies that enhance thermostablity</text>
<text top="492" left="112" width="385" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">of enzymes both in vivo and in vitro are also assessed. Moreover, this review deals with efforts made</text>
<text top="503" left="112" width="323" height="9" font="font13" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="18" tag_type="text">on developing vectors for expressing recombinant enzymes in thermophilic hosts.</text>
<text top="553" left="55" width="60" height="10" font="font12" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="19" tag_type="title">Background</text>
<text top="564" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t28" reading_order_no="34" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">Thermostable enzymes and microorganisms have been</text>
<text top="576" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t29" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">topics for much research during the last two decades, but</text>
<text top="588" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">the interest in thermophiles and how their proteins are<i>in vivo </i></text>
<text top="599" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">able to function at elevated temperatures actually started</text>
<text top="611" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">as early as in the 1960's by the pioneering work of Brock<i>in vitro </i></text>
<text top="623" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">and his colleagues [1]. Microorganisms are, based on their</text>
<text top="635" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">optimal growth temperatures, divided into three main</text>
<text top="647" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">groups, i.e . psychrophiles (below 20°C), mesophiles<b>Background</b></text>
<text top="658" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">(moderate temperatures), and thermophiles (high tem-</text>
<text top="670" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t37" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">peratures, above 55°C) [2]. Only few eukaryotes are</text>
<text top="682" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">known to grow above this temperature, but some fungi</text>
<text top="694" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">grow in the temperature range 50 – 55°C [3]. Several years</text>
<text top="705" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">ago Kristjansson and Stetter [4], suggested a further divi-</text>
<text top="717" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">sion of the thermophiles and a hyperthermophile bound-<a href="">lleagues [1]</a>. Microorganisms are, based on their</text>
<text top="729" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="21" tag_type="text">ary (growth at and above 80°C) that has today reached</text>
<text top="553" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="20" tag_type="text">general acceptance. Most thermophilic bacteria character-</text>
<text top="564" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="20" tag_type="text">ised today grow below the hyperthermophilic boundary<i>i.e</i></text>
<text top="576" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="51" segment_no="20" tag_type="text">(with some exceptions, such as Thermotoga and Aquifex</text>
<text top="588" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="52" segment_no="20" tag_type="text">[5]) while hyperthermophilic species are dominated by</text>
<text top="599" left="313" width="52" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="53" segment_no="20" tag_type="text">the Archaea.<a href="">5°C) [2]. On</a>ly few eukaryotes are</text>
<text top="623" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">Use and development of molecular biology techniques,</text>
<text top="635" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="55" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">permitting genetic analysis and gene transfer for recom-<a href="">°C [3]. Sever</a>al years</text>
<text top="647" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="56" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">binant production, led to dramatically increased activities<a href="">4</a>], suggested a further divi-</text>
<text top="658" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="57" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">in the field of thermostable enzymes during the 1990's.</text>
<text top="670" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t52" reading_order_no="58" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">This also stimulated isolation of a number of microbes</text>
<text top="682" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t53" reading_order_no="59" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">from thermal environments in order to access enzymes</text>
<text top="694" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t54" reading_order_no="60" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">that could significantly increase the window for enzy-</text>
<text top="705" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t55" reading_order_no="61" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">matic bioprocess operations. One of the early successful</text>
<text top="717" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t56" reading_order_no="62" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">commercialised examples was analytical use of a ther-<i>Thermotoga </i></text>
<text top="729" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font15" id="p1_t57" reading_order_no="63" segment_no="22" tag_type="text">mostable enzyme, Taq -polymerase, in polymerase chain</text>
<text top="254" left="55" width="83" height="7" font="font17" id="p1_t58" reading_order_no="11" segment_no="10" tag_type="text">Published: 15 March 2007<i>Aquifex</i></text>
<text top="268" left="55" width="102" height="7" font="font18" id="p1_t59" reading_order_no="12" segment_no="13" tag_type="text">Microbial Cell Factories 2007, 6 :9<a href="">[5]) </a>while hyperthermophilic species are dominated by</text>
<text top="268" left="166" width="88" height="7" font="font17" id="p1_t60" reading_order_no="13" segment_no="13" tag_type="text">doi:10.1186/1475-2859-6-9</text>
